[[Image:Image-sipapu.JPG|thumb|right|300px|The sipapu/<shibapu>{{angle bracket|}} is the small round hole in the floor of the kiva ruin. The larger round hole in the floor is a fire pit. Observe that the air intake (little rectangular door in the wall), the stones that block air from the air intake, the fire pit and the sipapu are all in a line; this aspect of the design was intentional. Photo taken at Long House, [[Mesa Verde National Park]].]] '''''Sipapu''''' is a [[Hopi language|Hopi]] word for a small hole or indentation in the floor of a ''[[kiva]]'' or pithouse.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://google.com/|title=Google|website=google.com|language=en|access-date=2017-10-05}}</ref> Kivas were used by the [[Ancestral Puebloans]] and continue to be used by modern-day [[Pueblo people|Puebloans]]. The ''sipapu'' symbolizes the portal through which their ancient ancestors [[Hopi mythology#Four Worlds|first emerged]] to enter the present world.<ref>{{cite book |last=Wenger |first=Gilbert R. |title=The Story of Mesa Verde National Park |publisher=Mesa Verde Museum Association |location=[[Mesa Verde National Park]], Colorado |year=1991 |orig-year=1980 |isbn=0-937062-15-4}}</ref>
Moreover, The Hopi Sacred Stories explain that this is the hole in which the first peoples of this world entered. As "They" stepped outside of the "Sipapu", they changed from lizard-like beings into homo sapiens, or human form (See Waters, 1963, and later reprints; Courlander, 1971). It is from this point that the "First Peoples" of the Earth began to divide and separate, creating differing tribes along the first journeys of the first humans. {{expand section|date=June 2015}}
==See also==
* [[Sipapu (ski area)|Sipapu]] (ski area)
==References== {{refimprove|date=June 2015}} {{Reflist}}
* Waters, F. (1963). "Book of the Hopis". New York: Penguin Group. * Courlander, H. (1971). "The Fourth World of the Hopis." Albuquerque, University of New Mexico Press.
sando,joe s,(1982). "the pueblo indians". san francisco; the Indian historian press.
[[Category:Native American religion]] [[Category:Puebloan architectural elements]]
{{Culture-stub}} {{NorthAm-native-stub}}
The Hopi and other Pueblo Culture people (Zuni, Acoma) believe that they are born of the Grand Canyon which is where the original Sipapu is located. The Grand Canyon is the 'place of emergence' and each modern Hopi village would have one or several kivas. Each kiva is subterranean and contains a small hole, just off center, to represent their place of emergence for religious purpose.

{{Refimprove|date=February 2018}}
{{merge to|King Mosiah II|discuss=Talk:Sons of Mosiah#Merger proposal|date=July 2018}}

<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lds.org/scriptures/bofm/mosiah/27.34?lang=eng#p33|title=Mosiah 27|website=www.lds.org|access-date=2017-12-31}}</ref> The '''sons of Mosiah''' is the collective name used in the [[Book of Mormon]] for four sons of King [[King Mosiah II|Mosiah]], whose names were [[Ammon (Book of Mormon)#Ammon²|Ammon]], [[Aaron (Nephite)|Aaron]], [[Omner]], and [[Himni]].  These sons were notable for their initial opposition to the church, their miraculous repentance and conversion to Christ.  They subsequently served as missionaries among the [[Lamanites]], accompanied by their friends Muloki and Ammah.

